But just let me deal with
the insurance company,

14:18.090 --> 14:20.149
I'm gonna work it out,
let's just stay focused on Dad.

14:20.270 --> 14:21.817
All right?

14:21.930 --> 14:24.194
Don't worry about it.

14:28.170 --> 14:29.990
Camille: Oh, Amber.

14:30.110 --> 14:32.897
I just remembered. Tonight's
your--your baby shower.

14:33.010 --> 14:34.272
Amber: That's--no, no.
Camille: What?

14:34.390 --> 14:35.698
Sarah: My God, we didn't even
think about--

14:35.800 --> 14:37.244
Amber: We're not, yeah--
Camille: No, you have to go.

14:37.350 --> 14:38.931
Amber: It's not happening.
Camille: Your mom paid for it.

14:39.050 --> 14:40.312
You shouldn't lose all
that money.

14:40.430 --> 14:41.499
Sarah: It's mostly just us
anyway.

14:41.600 --> 14:42.385
Amber: Yeah, Grandma.
Sarah: Just try to see

14:42.500 --> 14:43.979
if we can switch it
to another nIght.

14:44.090 --> 14:45.216
Amber: It's fine.
Hank: I can call the guy

14:45.330 --> 14:46.319
if you want--I can do that.
Sarah: That's okay.

14:46.430 --> 14:47.533
Kristina: I actually know him,
I can call him.

14:47.640 --> 14:49.983
He worked with me on the
campaign and catering and stuff.

14:50.090 --> 14:51.398
Sarah: Yeah. If you don't mind.
Maybe.

14:51.510 --> 14:52.704
Hank: Okay, if you know him,
you do it.

14:52.820 --> 14:53.912
Kristina: I do.
Yeah, I know him.

14:54.030 --> 14:56.021
Sarah: Don't worry about it,
okay?

14:56.130 --> 14:58.405
Kristina: Done. Hey.
Adam: Hey. Any news?

14:58.510 --> 15:00.023
Amber: Hey, what happened?
Kristina: Hi.

15:00.140 --> 15:02.404
Adam: Uh, they took everything.
Crosby: Everything's

15:02.520 --> 15:05.728
trashed and broken.
[overlapping murmuring]

15:05.830 --> 15:06.967
Adam: Nothing to be done
about it now.

15:07.070 --> 15:08.514
Jasmine: Sorry.
Crosby: Yeah.

15:08.630 --> 15:10.860
Camille: Oh, Leland.

15:10.970 --> 15:12.597
Leland, thank you so much
for coming.

15:12.700 --> 15:15.453
Dr. Gordon: Of course, of course
I'm gonna be here.

15:15.560 --> 15:17.972
He's had a pretty bad setback.
Camille: Right.

15:18.080 --> 15:19.490
Dr. Gordon: We're still trying
to pinpoint exactly

15:19.600 --> 15:22.489
what happened. Right now, we're
waiting to see how he responds

15:22.610 --> 15:24.919
to the medical therapy that
we've already given him.

15:25.020 --> 15:27.648
We just want to make sure his
heart, his lungs, his kidneys,

15:27.750 --> 15:30.856
are as strong as possible before
we consider any more treatment.

15:30.960 --> 15:32.302
Camille: What kind of treatment?

15:32.410 --> 15:34.446
Dr. Gordon: Um, it could be
as simple as taking him up

15:34.550 --> 15:36.711
into the cath lab _
and putting some stents In.

15:36.830 --> 15:38.889
Camille: Okay.
Dr. Gordon: But...

15:39.000 --> 15:40.729
if the valve is part
of the problem,

15:40.830 --> 15:43.276
we're probably going to have to
go back in surgically

15:43.390 --> 15:44.721
and repair it.
Camille: Oh--oh, no.

15:44.840 --> 15:46.455
Dr. Gordon: I know. I know.
I wish I could tell you

15:46.560 --> 15:48.482
that everything's gonna be
all right.

15:48.600 --> 15:50.761
We're just going to have to
take one step at a time,

15:50.880 --> 15:53.599
so be patient with us until
we can figure it all out.

15:53.710 --> 15:56.087
He's stable in the meantime.
You can visit him in the ICU.

15:56.190 --> 15:59.227
[soft piano music]

16:03.100 --> 16:09.061
[melancholy singing]

16:09.170 --> 16:10.899
Camille: Zeek?
Zeek: [grunts]

16:11.000 --> 16:13.889
Camille: We're all here.

16:14.000 --> 16:15.888
Adam: You're gonna be okay, Pop.

16:17.660 --> 16:18.934
Crosby: Hey, Dad.

16:19.040 --> 16:24.592
[melancholy singing]

16:35.990 --> 16:39.266
[low chatter]

16:42.760 --> 16:43.749
Julia: Hey.
Adam: Hey.

16:47.070 --> 16:48.719
Adam: It's pretty rough
in there.

16:50.040 --> 16:51.894
Julia: Okay.

16:52.010 --> 16:53.341
Joel: I'll go in with you.

16:53.460 --> 16:54.836
Julia: Thanks.
nurse: I'm sorry,

16:54.940 --> 16:56.760
It's family members only.

16:56.870 --> 16:58.622
Julia: He's my husband.

16:58.740 --> 17:00.594
nurse: Okay. This way.

17:07.230 --> 17:12.406
[breathing machines]
[heart monitor]

17:18.930 --> 17:21.273
Julia: Hey, Pop.

17:23.900 --> 17:26.869
Hey, Joe! and I are here.
[alarm, rapid beeping]

17:26.970 --> 17:28.722
Um...

17:28.840 --> 17:31.479
Julia: Is that--
What's happening?

17:31.600 --> 17:33.318
nurse: Step outside, please.
Julia: Can you--can you just--

17:33.430 --> 17:35.660
Can you just give me--
doctor: What are his vitals?

17:35.770 --> 17:36.737
nurse: He's in V-fib.

17:36.840 --> 17:41.083
doctor: Pull the crash cart.
Charge to 200.

17:43.820 --> 17:45.367
Camille: Zeek?

18:17.260 --> 18:18.466
Julia: They just took Dad
to the operating room!

18:18.580 --> 18:19.979
all: What?

18:20.090 --> 18:21.296
Julia: Just--just now.

18:21.410 --> 18:22.229
He lost consciousness
and then, I don't know,

18:22.340 --> 18:23.568
the machine started beeping
and--

18:23.680 --> 18:24.476
Sarah: What machine?

18:24.580 --> 18:25.717
Crosby: Did he have another
heart attack?

18:25.820 --> 18:27.515
Adam: Used it to shock him?
Julia: I don't know!

18:27.620 --> 18:28.894
Adam: What the hell's going on?

18:29.000 --> 18:30.854
Joel: They took him
to the cath lab.

18:30.970 --> 18:32.449
He had another heart attack.

18:32.550 --> 18:35.383
And then they were able to
normalize his heartbeat.

18:35.490 --> 18:38.209
They had to put stents in him,
so they took him away

18:38.320 --> 18:41.005
so that they could get blood
back to the heart, but...

18:41.120 --> 18:44.669
that's all I know.

18:44.770 --> 18:47.330
But they're on top of it.

18:52.990 --> 18:55.458
Hank: Hey, Drew, what are you,
getting a soda?

18:55.580 --> 18:58.572
Drew: Yeah.
Hank: Cafeteria.

19:05.000 --> 19:09.482
Listen, uh, your grandfather's
gonna be okay, so, you know,

19:11.770 --> 19:15.524
Drew: I think that you don't
actually really know that.

19:15.630 --> 19:17.518
Hank: You looked upset.
Just trying to stay positive,

19:17.630 --> 19:19.769
that's all.
Drew: I just messed up so bad

19:19.880 --> 19:21.666
the other day.

19:21.780 --> 19:24.806
He asked me not to _tell
my grandmother something that

19:24.920 --> 19:26.569
he was trying to plan for her.

19:26.680 --> 19:29.365
And then I just ratted him out.

19:29.470 --> 19:31.404
I think that's it. That's the
last thing he's gonna remember

19:31.510 --> 19:33.990
about me when he's--
Hank: No, no. Drew...

19:34.100 --> 19:36.136
Drew: Yeah, it is, it's like,
he's been there for me

19:36.240 --> 19:39.129
the whole time.
Way more than my dad.

19:39.240 --> 19:40.719
Way more than any of
these losers that

19:40.830 --> 19:43.719
my mom brings around.

19:49.980 --> 19:53.689
Hank: He ain't gonna be thinking
that you, he's...

19:53.810 --> 19:56.529
My daughter could tell me
that she hates me,

19:59.020 --> 20:03.957
If something happens, I'm not
gonna be thinking of that.

20:06.890 --> 20:11.850
I don't know if your Grandpa's
gonna be all right or not but...

20:11.960 --> 20:16.511
I know that I'm a parent, uh,
just like him.

20:16.620 --> 20:19.623
We don't hold on to any
of that stuff.

20:24.840 --> 20:26.523
Drew: Thanks.

20:34.680 --> 20:37.535
Adam: Hey.
Crosby: Hey.

20:37.650 --> 20:39.572
Adam: Just got off the phone
with the insurance company.

20:39.680 --> 20:40.851
Crosby: Oh, yeah?
Adam: Yeah.

20:40.960 --> 20:42.609
Crosby: More great news?

20:42.720 --> 20:45.063
Adam: Yeah, actually, uh, the
numbers really worked out

20:45.170 --> 20:46.512
in our favor. It's a--
Crosby: Really?

20:46.620 --> 20:49.544
Adam: Much bigger payout
than I expected. Way more.

20:49.660 --> 20:52.242
Crosby: Like, we could replace
all the equipment big or...

20:52.350 --> 20:55.456
Adam: Yeah. Yeah.

20:55.560 --> 20:57.448
Crosby: Yeah, or what?

20:57.560 --> 21:01.906
Adam: Well, we can do that or,
um, we have another alternative.

21:02.010 --> 21:05.184
Just--just hear me out.
We could cash out.

21:05.290 --> 21:06.917
Crosby: Cash out?
Adam: Yeah.

21:07.020 --> 21:09.113
Adam: Instead of reinvesting
in the equipment,

21:09.230 --> 21:11.391
we could take the insurance
money and dissolve the busmess,

21:11.510 --> 21:12.738
and after we pay off the debts
we'd still have

21:12.850 --> 21:14.477
some money left over.

21:14.580 --> 21:16.434
Look, Cros, I don't know if
we're over going to make

21:16.550 --> 21:19.269
The Luncheonette profitable
and this way,

21:19.380 --> 21:21.234
you know, we're off scot-free.

21:21.340 --> 21:22.272
And we'd even have enough
left over to

21:22.380 --> 21:23.517
give Amber some severance pay.

21:23.620 --> 21:25.895
But we take the money,
we can walk away,

21:26.000 --> 21:30.380
we can have a fresh start.

21:30.490 --> 21:33.766
Crosby: Wow. Um...

21:33.870 --> 21:35.929
yeah, I mean, I guess...

21:36.050 --> 21:39.941
it makes sense_...it_ seems like
maybe a blessnng In dIngIse,

21:40.050 --> 21:42.735
but it's such a--and so quick.

21:42.850 --> 21:46.434
Yesterday, we had a business.
Now we're talking about--

21:48.090 --> 21:49.409
I'll think about it?

21:49.510 --> 21:50.716
Adam: Yeah, for sure, of course.
I--you know--

21:50.820 --> 21:52.094
I don't want you to do anything
you don't want to do

21:52.200 --> 21:53.781
and, you know, we're partners.

21:53.890 --> 21:56.450
Crosby: Okay.
Adam: So yeah, think about it.

21:56.550 --> 21:57.346
Crosby: Hmm...
Adam: Now we both will.

21:57.450 --> 22:00.578
Crosby: All right.
Adam: All right.

22:00.690 --> 22:01.679
Hey.

22:01.800 --> 22:03.688
[Camille breathing heavily]
- What?

22:03.800 --> 22:05.552
Camille: They put in the stents.

22:05.660 --> 22:07.457
He made it through.

22:07.560 --> 22:09.380
Adam: Oh, okay, good, Mom, good.
Camille: [crying]

22:09.500 --> 22:11.809
Adam: Okay. All right.

22:11.910 --> 22:13.593
You all right? You okay?

22:13.710 --> 22:15.849
Camille: Yeah. He's stable.

22:15.950 --> 22:17.497
Crosby: He's stable.
Camille: He's stable.

22:17.610 --> 22:19.635
Adam: Mm, okay, good.

22:19.750 --> 22:21.570
Crosby: It's okay, Mom.

22:39.180 --> 22:41.626
Zeek: Hey.

22:41.730 --> 22:44.426
Oh, boy.

22:44.530 --> 22:47.567
That wasn't a banner day,
was it?

22:47.670 --> 22:49.490
Adam: Oh, Dad, you're a fighter.

22:49.600 --> 22:52.012
Crosby: Yeah, you're a beast,
Dad. You came through.

22:52.120 --> 22:53.747
Sarah: You kept us on our toes.

22:53.850 --> 22:55.158
Julia: Yeah, that was exciting,
Dad.

22:55.270 --> 22:56.578
Sarah: Mm-hmm.

22:56.680 --> 23:01.128
Camille: Do you wanna rest now?
Zeek: Uh...

23:01.240 --> 23:03.686
No, stay.

23:03.790 --> 23:06.167
Okay?

23:06.280 --> 23:09.443
Camille.

23:09.560 --> 23:11.653
Oh, Cammy.

23:17.080 --> 23:19.457
Crosby: So I climb up the side
of the house, right?

23:19.570 --> 23:22.186
And over the balcony--
I slide in through the window,

23:22.290 --> 23:24.463
I'm trying to be quiet but I'm
three sheets to the wind

23:24.570 --> 23:25.605
and I smell like a brewery.

23:25.710 --> 23:28.178
And when I left I had put
pillows under the sheets

23:28.300 --> 23:29.153
to fool everyone.
[laughter]

23:29.260 --> 23:30.192
Sarah: Classic!

23:30.300 --> 23:31.608
Crosby: And I get undressed,

23:31.720 --> 23:34.473
and I'm sliding into bed
and I feel human skin,

23:34.580 --> 23:36.502
and Dad pops out!
[laughter]

23:36.620 --> 23:38.850
And he goes,
"Expecting someone else?"

23:38.960 --> 23:40.518
[laughter]

23:40.620 --> 23:42.372
Crosby: How long were you
laying there?

23:42.490 --> 23:43.969
Zeek: I don't know,
it was forever, I think.

23:44.070 --> 23:45.697
Crosby: I thought there was
a corpse in the bed!

23:45.800 --> 23:47.836
Zeek: God, the look on your face
though, Cros.

23:47.940 --> 23:49.862
Crosby: [laughs] It scared
the crap out of me.

23:49.980 --> 23:51.663
[knock on door]

23:51.770 --> 23:52.805
Dr. Gordon: Sorry, am I
interrupting?

23:52.910 --> 23:55.595
All: No.
Zeek: Hey, Leland, come on in.

23:55.710 --> 23:56.779
Dr. Gordon: There he is.
Zeek: Oh, man,

23:56.880 --> 23:59.633
I am so sorry about getting you
up so early.

23:59.740 --> 24:02.743
Dr. Gordon: Oh, come on now.
You kidding me?

24:02.850 --> 24:06.297
Zeek: So, uh, how am I?

24:06.410 --> 24:07.980
Dr. Gordon: Um...

24:08.100 --> 24:09.544
it's okay to...talk?
Adam: You want us to leave?

24:09.650 --> 24:10.878
Dr. Gordon: No, no!
It's up to him.

24:11.000 --> 24:12.547
Zeek: We're in this together
here.

24:12.650 --> 24:14.754
Dr. Gordon: Okay, no.

24:14.860 --> 24:16.543
All right, well, look.
We've always been straight

24:16.660 --> 24:18.173
with each other, right?
Zeek: Yeah.

24:18.280 --> 24:21.556
Dr. Gordon: And we tell it like
it is. Okay, first of all,

24:21.660 --> 24:24.311
the stents we put in were
successful.

24:24.420 --> 24:31.280
But your heart, Zeek, is just
not as strong as it needs to be.

24:31.400 --> 24:34.085
You're still getting fluid
backing up into your lungs,

24:34.190 --> 24:37.774
and that's what started all of
this to begin with.

24:37.890 --> 24:42.782
So, um, option one:
we go back in.

24:42.890 --> 24:45.267
We open you up again and we
fix the valve.

24:45.380 --> 24:48.235
Replace the damn thing if we
have to.

24:48.340 --> 24:49.750
The problem is you're not as
strong as you were

24:53.110 --> 24:57.035
Opening you back up again could
be a very dangerous thing.

25:00.080 --> 25:03.140
Zeek: Okay, uh, so what
if I don't do anything?

25:03.260 --> 25:05.637
Dr. Gordon: Well,
then you run the risks.

25:05.740 --> 25:10.154
Another heart attack.
Or blood clots. Or a stroke.

25:10.260 --> 25:13.195
Aneurysm.
Zeek: All right...

25:13.300 --> 25:16.428
Okay, so, I've got a couple
of options and

25:16.540 --> 25:18.929
neither one of them sound pretty
good to me.

25:19.030 --> 25:23.239
Dr. Gordon: Okay.
Option three.

25:23.340 --> 25:25.797
Take some time.

25:25.900 --> 25:27.686
Rest up.

25:27.800 --> 25:29.688
Talk to the family.

25:29.800 --> 25:31.859
I'm sure you'll have lots of
questions and I promise you,

25:31.970 --> 25:35.007
you will talk about all of them.

25:38.600 --> 25:41.569
Zeek: Okay. Thanks, Leland.
Dr. Gordon: Yeah.

25:44.500 --> 25:46.149
Jasmine: Hey, we were looking
for you.

25:46.260 --> 25:49.957
Crosby: Hey. Yeah, I needed to
take a minute.

25:50.060 --> 25:51.539
Jasmine: I bet.

25:51.650 --> 25:54.232
He's gonna pull through, baby.

25:54.340 --> 25:55.989
I know he will.

25:56.100 --> 25:57.613
Crosby: You should've heard what
they were saying in there.

25:57.720 --> 26:01.235
It was...far from positive.

26:07.910 --> 26:09.935
_ Adam talked to
the Insurance company and--

26:10.050 --> 26:12.518
Jasmine: Really?
Crosby: Looks like they're gonna

26:12.640 --> 26:14.494
give us a big ol' check.

26:14.600 --> 26:16.739
Jasmine: Oh, that's fantastic.

26:16.850 --> 26:19.011
Crosby: Yeah.
Jasmine: That's good.

26:19.120 --> 26:21.293
Crosby: Yeah...

26:21.400 --> 26:23.334
he thinks we should take the
money and just keep it, move,

26:23.440 --> 26:24.987
and break our lease.

26:25.100 --> 26:27.409
Pay off our debts, he thinks we
can both walk away

26:27.510 --> 26:30.855
with like 20 grand even after
giving Amber some money.

26:30.960 --> 26:33.019
Jasmine: Mmm...
Crosby: Shut up shop.

26:33.140 --> 26:34.823
Jasmine: Hmm...

26:34.930 --> 26:36.818
Crosby: We could take the kid
to Hogwarts.

26:36.940 --> 26:42.549
And I could get a job a Bawiew,
they're always calling.

26:42.670 --> 26:48.631
It'd be a lot of pressure off
me and us.

26:48.740 --> 26:50.708
Jasmine: It would.

26:50.810 --> 26:52.459
Crosby: He thinks it's
a no-brainer.

26:52.570 --> 26:55.050
Jasmine: Hmm.

26:55.160 --> 26:56.957
What do you think?

27:00.890 --> 27:04.826
Crosby: I think it's been a
really stressful year

27:04.930 --> 27:08.229
and the idea of not having any
stress right now

27:08.350 --> 27:10.682
sounds pretty good.

27:10.800 --> 27:13.382
Jasmine: Okay.

27:13.490 --> 27:16.971
Crosby: What do you think?

27:17.080 --> 27:20.868
Jasmine: I think I'll support
you no matter what.

27:20.980 --> 27:24.905
But you've already tried working
for other people

27:25.020 --> 27:29.536
and you were miserable.
And I don't want that.

27:29.640 --> 27:32.200
The Luncheonette,
that made you happy.

27:32.300 --> 27:33.881
That was your dream.

27:33.990 --> 27:36.788
And you can't let these jerks
that broke in

27:36.890 --> 27:39.859
or some slow months of business
or even Adam

27:39.960 --> 27:42.849
take that away from you.

27:42.970 --> 27:44.619
Life is short, baby.

27:44.730 --> 27:47.039
You gotta hang in there.

27:57.570 --> 27:59.902
Drew: Hey, can I sit down?

28:00.020 --> 28:03.911
Hank: Yeah.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, sit.

28:10.550 --> 28:13.951
That Joel.
He's, like...

28:14.070 --> 28:16.823
not even married
and he's the perfect husband.

28:16.930 --> 28:19.967
Right? He brings coffee,
he knows the medical jargon,

28:20.070 --> 28:21.753
he's...

28:21.870 --> 28:24.009
I mean, he's in pretty good
shape.

28:24.110 --> 28:26.795
He doesn't even eat well, I saw
him at the candy thing he--

28:26.910 --> 28:28.047
he was getting Twizzlers.

28:28.150 --> 28:31.005
So it's not like
he's a health guy.

28:31.120 --> 28:34.942
And I don't even hate him for
it, he's a good guy.

28:35.050 --> 28:38.019
I'm sorry, man.
I'm ranting.

28:38.130 --> 28:40.985
I do that. I just rant when I
get nervous. I just, uh--

28:41.090 --> 28:43.024
Drew: It's fine, I don't care.

28:43.130 --> 28:48.193
Hank: I'm just a little--I'm not
that--I'm nervous--I'm just--

28:48.310 --> 28:52.030
I'm just--I just, I wanna be
there for your mom.

28:52.140 --> 28:55.894
I don't wanna be, uh, one of
the losers and--

28:56.010 --> 28:57.341
uh, I'm sorry, look, this is not
your problem.

28:57.450 --> 28:59.554
Why am I even talking?
Just tell me to shut up.

28:59.660 --> 29:02.902
You can--look, I know I'm an
adult but you can just--

29:03.010 --> 29:06.116
smack me or punch me in the
neck, anything you wanna do.

29:06.220 --> 29:08.871
Kick me in the slacks.
I don't care.

29:08.980 --> 29:11.699
Drew: I'm really sorry about
that--saying the thing

29:11.810 --> 29:13.983
about the losers.
I don't mean that.

29:14.090 --> 29:16.604
I'm serious. I was just stressed
and really upset

29:16.720 --> 29:20.611
about everything and--
Hank: I appreciate it. Thanks.

29:20.720 --> 29:25.020
Drew: You know,
I really like you a lot.

29:25.140 --> 29:29.827
Probably my favorite guy that
my mom's brought around.

29:29.940 --> 29:32.829
Hank: [laughs]
I'm your favorite? I guess--

29:32.940 --> 29:34.316
I'm your favorite loser of
all those ones.

29:34.420 --> 29:36.240
